{
  "What is terminal velocity?": "",
  "The maximum constant speed a falling object reaches": "",
  "The initial speed of an object when it starts falling": "",
  "The speed at which an object is first thrown upward": "",
  "The speed of sound through the air at ground level": "",
  "Terminal velocity is the maximum constant speed reached by a falling object when the upward force of air resistance equals the downward force of gravity. At this point, acceleration becomes zero.": "",
  "What two forces are balanced when an object reaches terminal velocity?": "",
  "Friction and the applied pushing force": "",
  "Gravity and air resistance (drag force)": "",
  "Magnetism and the electric force on it": "",
  "Tension and the normal contact force": "",
  "Terminal velocity occurs when the downward pull of gravity equals the upward push of air resistance. When these forces balance, the net force is zero and the object stops accelerating.": "",
  "What is the acceleration of an object at terminal velocity?": "",
  "It equals 9.8 meters per second squared": "",
  "It is increasing at a steady constant rate": "",
  "It is zero because the forces are balanced": "",
  "It is negative and still decreasing rapidly": "",
  "At terminal velocity, gravity and air resistance are equal and opposite, so the net force is zero. According to Newton's second law, if net force is zero, acceleration is also zero.": "",
  "As a skydiver falls, what happens to air resistance before terminal velocity is reached?": "",
  "Air resistance stays constant the whole time": "",
  "Air resistance decreases as speed increases": "",
  "Air resistance has no effect on the fall": "",
  "Air resistance increases as speed increases": "",
  "As a falling object speeds up, it pushes through more air per second, so air resistance increases. It keeps increasing until it equals gravity, at which point terminal velocity is reached.": "",
  "Which object would have a lower terminal velocity: a feather or a bowling ball?": "",
  "A feather, because it has a large surface area relative to its weight": "",
  "A bowling ball, because it is much heavier than the feather": "",
  "Both have the same terminal velocity regardless of properties": "",
  "Neither reaches terminal velocity when falling in the air": "",
  "A feather has a large surface area compared to its weight, so air resistance balances gravity at a much lower speed. A bowling ball is heavy and compact, so it must fall much faster before air resistance can balance gravity.": "",
  "How does opening a parachute affect terminal velocity?": "",
  "It increases terminal velocity significantly": "",
  "It has no effect on terminal velocity at all": "",
  "It greatly decreases terminal velocity": "",
  "It eliminates gravity on the skydiver": "",
  "A parachute greatly increases the surface area catching air, which increases air resistance. This means air resistance balances gravity at a much lower speed, greatly decreasing the terminal velocity.": "",
  "Does a heavier object generally have a higher or lower terminal velocity than a lighter one of the same shape?": "",
  "Lower, because heavier objects fall more slowly": "",
  "Higher, because more air resistance is needed to balance gravity": "",
  "The same, because weight does not affect terminal velocity": "",
  "Neither, because heavier objects cannot reach terminal velocity": "",
  "A heavier object has a greater gravitational force pulling it down. Air resistance must match this larger force, which only happens at higher speeds. So a heavier object of the same shape has a higher terminal velocity.": "",
  "What happens to a falling object's speed after it reaches terminal velocity?": "",
  "It continues to increase without any limit": "",
  "It decreases slowly until the object stops": "",
  "It remains constant and does not change": "",
  "It oscillates between fast and slow speeds": "",
  "Once terminal velocity is reached, the forces are balanced and acceleration is zero. The object continues falling at the same constant speed. It does not speed up or slow down.": "",
  "Which factor does NOT affect an object's terminal velocity?": "",
  "The object's surface area facing the wind": "",
  "The object's weight or gravitational force": "",
  "The color of the object that is falling": "",
  "The density of the air the object falls through": "",
  "Terminal velocity depends on weight, surface area, shape, and air density. The color of the object has no effect on the forces of gravity or air resistance, so it does not affect terminal velocity.": "",
  "When a skydiver first jumps from a plane, is the acceleration closer to 9.8 m/s squared or 0 m/s squared?": "",
  "The acceleration is zero from the very start": "",
  "The acceleration starts close to 9.8 m/s squared": "",
  "The acceleration is exactly 4.9 m/s squared": "",
  "The acceleration starts at negative 9.8 m/s sq": "",
  "When first jumping, the skydiver has very low speed, so air resistance is minimal. Gravity dominates, making acceleration close to 9.8 m/s squared. As speed increases, air resistance grows and acceleration decreases toward zero.": "",
  "The constant speed where air resistance equals gravity during a fall": "",
  "The speed at which an object bounces back upward after hitting ground": "",
  "The maximum speed an object can ever reach in any situation at all": "",
  "The initial velocity when an object first starts falling from a height": "",
  "Terminal velocity is the constant speed a falling object reaches when the upward air resistance force exactly equals the downward gravitational force. At this point, the net force and acceleration are both zero.": "",
  "What does 'air resistance' mean?": "",
  "The force of gravity pulling objects downward": "",
  "The friction-like force air exerts on moving objects": "",
  "The weight of the air above an object on Earth": "",
  "The amount of oxygen available for breathing": "",
  "Air resistance (also called drag) is the force that air exerts on a moving object, opposing its motion. It acts like friction and increases with the speed and surface area of the object.": "",
  "What does 'drag force' mean?": "",
  "The force that pushes an object forward": "",
  "The resistance force opposing motion through a fluid": "",
  "The gravitational pull between two large masses": "",
  "The elastic force from a compressed spring": "",
  "Drag force is the resistance force that opposes an object's motion through a fluid such as air or water. It depends on the object's speed, shape, size, and the density of the fluid.": "",
  "What does 'net force' mean in the context of terminal velocity?": "",
  "The total combined force after adding all forces together": "",
  "Only the force of gravity acting on the falling object": "",
  "Only the air resistance acting on the falling object": "",
  "The mass of the object multiplied by its total volume": "",
  "Net force is the vector sum of all forces acting on an object. At terminal velocity, the net force is zero because gravity (downward) and air resistance (upward) are equal and opposite.": "",
  "What does 'surface area' mean in relation to terminal velocity?": "",
  "The total outside area of an object exposed to the air": "",
  "The volume of air inside a hollow falling object": "",
  "The weight of the object in newtons or pounds": "",
  "The speed at which the object is currently falling": "",
  "Surface area is the total outside area of an object. A larger surface area catches more air, creating greater air resistance. This is why a parachute (large surface area) slows a skydiver down.": "",
  "What does 'free fall' mean?": "",
  "Falling with only gravity acting, with no air resistance": "",
  "Falling at terminal velocity through the atmosphere": "",
  "Falling and then bouncing back up off the ground": "",
  "Falling very slowly through a thick liquid material": "",
  "Free fall is when an object falls under the influence of gravity alone, with no air resistance. In true free fall (like in a vacuum), all objects accelerate at the same rate regardless of mass.": "",
  "What is meant by 'balanced forces' at terminal velocity?": "",
  "Forces that are equal in size but opposite in direction": "",
  "Forces that push the object in the same single direction": "",
  "Forces that change the acceleration of the object": "",
  "Forces that exist only when the object is at rest": "",
  "Balanced forces are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction, resulting in a net force of zero. At terminal velocity, gravity pulling down and air resistance pushing up are balanced forces.": "",
  "What does 'fluid density' mean in the context of terminal velocity?": "",
  "The speed at which a fluid flows past the object": "",
  "How tightly packed the particles of a fluid are": "",
  "The color and temperature of the surrounding fluid": "",
  "The total amount of fluid in a given container": "",
  "Fluid density is the mass per unit volume of the fluid. Denser fluids (like water versus air) create more resistance, which means terminal velocity is lower in denser fluids.": "",
  "What does 'streamlined' mean in relation to air resistance?": "",
  "Having a shape designed to reduce air resistance": "",
  "Having a very large and flat surface area": "",
  "Being painted a bright color for high visibility": "",
  "Moving at the slowest possible speed always": "",
  "A streamlined shape is smooth and tapered to allow air to flow around it easily, reducing drag. Race cars, airplanes, and birds have streamlined shapes to minimize air resistance.": "",
  "What does 'cross-sectional area' mean for a falling object?": "",
  "The total weight of the object during the fall": "",
  "The area of the object as seen from the direction of motion": "",
  "The volume of the entire falling object in cubic meters": "",
  "The distance the object has fallen from its start": "",
  "Cross-sectional area is the area of the object as seen from the direction it is moving. A larger cross-sectional area means more air is pushed aside, creating greater drag and a lower terminal velocity.": "",
